c tradition has not yet been scrutinised in detail. This volume addresses this desideratum and combines case studies from both traditions of geographic thinking. The contributions comprise in-depth analyses of individual geographical works as for example those of al-Idrisi or Lambert of Saint-Omer, different forms of presenting geographical knowledge such as TO-diagrams or globes as well as performative aspects of studying and meditating geographical knowledge. Focussing on texts as well as on maps, the contributions open up a comparative perspective on how religious knowledge influenced the way the world and its geography were perceived and described int the medieval world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGeography.  acartography.  areligion.1 aBaumgärtner, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouloux, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDucène, Jean-Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtienne Du Bois, Raoul Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerro, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranz, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauntel, Christoph , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMauntel, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinto, Karen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmieder, Felicitas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchröder, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct